Introduction¶

The objective of this notebook is to explore various machine learning model approaches for a 'ham versus spam' classification of SMS text messages. The messages are sourced from a publicly available dataset on Kaggle along with their labels, so I will be creating models in a supervised learning setting.

Feature Engineering¶

I start with creating features to better understand the text (i.e. do spam messages tend to have more numbers or capital letters?). Too many features leads to overfitting but for exploratory data analysis, it may be useful.

In [3]:
def feature_engineering(df, target_column):
    # count number of characters in target column (this includes whitespace)
    df['Number of Characters'] = df[target_column].apply(len)

    # count number of words
    df['Number of Words'] = df[target_column].apply(word_count)
    
    # average word length per target column cell
    df['Average Word Length'] = df[target_column].apply(avg_word_length)
    
    # calculating the number of capital letters
    df['Number of Capital Letters'] = df[target_column].apply(num_capital_letters)
    
    # calculating the number of digits
    df['Number of Digits'] = df[target_column].apply(num_digits)
    
    # calculating the number of punctuations
    df['Number of Punctuation Marks'] = df[target_column].apply(count_punct)
    
    # calculating the percent of punctuations
    df['Percentage of Punctuation'] = df[target_column].apply(count_punct_percentage)
    
    # calculating the number of syllables
    df['Number of Syllables'] = df[target_column].apply(syllable_count)
    
    # calculating the number of polysyllables (words with greater than 3 or more syllables) 
    df['Number of Words with Polysyllables'] = df[target_column].apply(polysyllable_count)

# functions to create features
def word_count(string):
    words = string.split()
    return len(words)

def avg_word_length(string):
    words = string.split()
    word_length = [len(word) for word in words]
    avg_word_length = sum(word_length)/len(words)
    return avg_word_length

def num_capital_letters(string):
    return len(re.findall(r'[A-Z]', string))

def num_digits(string):
    return len(re.findall(r'[0-9]', string))

def count_punct(text):
    count = sum([1 for char in text if char in string.punctuation])
    return count

def count_punct_percentage(text):
    count = sum([1 for char in text if char in string.punctuation])
    return round(count/(len(text) - text.count(" ")), 3)*100

def syllable_count(text):
    return tstat.sybl_counts(text)['sybl_count']

def polysyllable_count(text):
    return tstat.sybl_counts(text)['polysyblword_count']

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

In [5]:
# a function to create a wordcloud
def create_wordcloud(df, label):
    wc = WordCloud(background_color = "white", width = 1600, height = 800).generate(' '.join(df['text']))
    plt.imshow(wc)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout(pad=0)
    plt.title(f'Word Cloud for {label} Messages')
    plt.savefig(f'images/Word Cloud for {label} Messages.png', bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show()

# a function to create a barplot
def create_barplot(df, col):
    title = f'Mean {col}'
    sns.barplot(x = 'label', y = col, data = df).set_title(title)
    plt.savefig(f'images/{title}.png')
    plt.show()
    
# a function to create a violin (distribution) plot
def create_violinplot(df, col):
    title = f'{col} Distribution'
    sns.violinplot(x = col, y = 'label', data = df, orient = 'h').set_title(title)
    plt.savefig(f'images/{title}.png')
    plt.show()

Preprocessing Data¶

Code for preprocessing using SpaCy is referenced from a DataQuest article. I opted not to use their transformer code and added a list comprehension to process out non-alphabetical tokens.

In [12]:
# create our list of punctuation marks
punctuations = string.punctuation

# load in spaCy model and create a list of stopwords
nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')
stop_words = spacy.lang.en.stop_words.STOP_WORDS

# load English tokenizer, tagger, parser, NER and word vectors
parser = English()

# Creating our tokenizer function
def spacy_tokenizer(sentence):
    # Creating our token object, which is used to create documents with linguistic annotations.
    mytokens = parser(sentence)

    # Lemmatizing each token and converting each token into lowercase
    mytokens = [word.lemma_.lower().strip() if word.lemma_ != "-PRON-" else word.lower_ for word in mytokens]

    # Removing stop words
    mytokens = [word for word in mytokens if word not in stop_words and word not in punctuations]
    
    # Removing non-alphabetical tokens
    mytokens = [word for word in mytokens if word.isalpha()]

    # return preprocessed list of tokens
    return mytokens

Splitting Data into Training (70%) and Test (30%) sets¶

Some models require dense representations of the data (i.e. with column labels and indices). The default behavior of transforming the data using TF-IDF and standardization means we need to convert that data to a dense representation for specific models (Naive Bayes). This can be done by using the .toarray() or .todense() methods, although if our aim is to understand feature importances in models, another method is needed to restore feature names.

It should further be noted that StandardScaler from scikit-learn does not store feature names when our extra features are standardized. I have written some messy code to get around this, though I opted not to use it for this project.

In [13]:
le = LabelEncoder()
tfidf_vector = TfidfVectorizer(tokenizer = spacy_tokenizer)

X = df.drop(['label'], axis = 1)
y = le.fit_transform(df.label)
labels = list(le.classes_)
print("The labels are: ", labels)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 42)

# obtaining list of extraneous features
extra_features = X_train.drop(['text'], axis = 1).columns.tolist()

# preprocessing the data through a column transformer, the end result is a Sparse Matrix
ct = ColumnTransformer([('Tfidf Vectorizer', tfidf_vector, 'text'),
                        ('Standardization of Extra Features', StandardScaler(), extra_features)], 
                       remainder='passthrough')

# transforming training and test data by vectorizing text column and standardizing extra features
X_train_scaled = ct.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = ct.transform(X_test)

# storing train and test data into dense arrays for use in specific models
X_train_scaled_dense = X_train_scaled.todense()
X_test_scaled_dense = X_test_scaled.todense()

The labels are:  ['ham', 'spam']

An alternative way to keep features for use in feature_importances for models using Pandas DataFrames, indexing, and columns¶

I do not use a StandardScaler because it results in some negative values, which can't be used in our Naive Bayes model. Instead I use a MinMaxScaler that transforms our extra features between 0 and 1.

Modeling¶

Helper functions¶

In [15]:
# a function to print out classification report
def cr(y_test, y_pred, digits = 4):
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names = labels, digits = digits))

# helper function to print out classification report
def best_params(model, params, other = None):
    for key in params.keys():
        print('Best {}: '.format(key), model.best_estimator_.get_params()[key])
        
def grid_search(model, param_grid):
    # initializing grid
    grid = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid, cv = 5, verbose = 1, n_jobs = -1)
    
    # training model
    start_time = time.perf_counter()
    best_model = grid.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    end_time = time.perf_counter()
    train_time = (end_time - start_time) * 1000
    
    # outputting best parameters
    best_params(best_model, param_grid)
    
    # making predictions
    start_time = time.perf_counter()
    y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    end_time = time.perf_counter()
    predict_time = (end_time - start_time) * 1000
    
    # printing out classification report
    cr(y_test, y_pred)
    
    return best_model, train_time, predict_time

Interpreting Results¶

In this section, I visualize the training and prediction times. Additional metrics are provided such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F-scores (on the test data).

Helper Method¶

In [24]:
# a function to create barplots for each model
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(7,7)})
def create_model_barplot(data, col1, col2, title, lim):
    g = sns.barplot(data.iloc[:, col2], data.iloc[:, col1])
    ax = g
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate("%.2f" % p.get_height(), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                    ha='center', va='center', color='gray', xytext=(0, 20),
                    textcoords='offset points')
    g.set_ylim(0, lim)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.savefig(f'images/{title}.png', bbox_inches = "tight")
    plt.show()

    plt.savefig(f'images/{title}.png', bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show()

    recall_scores.append(recall_score(y_test, y_pred))

Conclusions¶

The training times for the models vary depending on how many parameters were searched for during our exhaustive Gridsearch. Under the cells for each model, we can find a print out of the number of fits required by each model.

The prediction times are a more consistent metric and is measured in milliseconds because of how fast it is. It is notable that if we are going for fast prediction times, we may opt for a Logistic Regression model or a Decision Tree Model. There is an argument to be made for trying other models based on the metrics they've achieved on the test data (30% of data that we held out).

Precision, Recall, and F-scores are the most imperative metrics for determining how good each model is. These metrics all range from 0 to 1 and mean different things. Precision is how good our model is at predicting the positive class. A high precision means that our models won't mistake ham labels as spam. If our training data consisted of emails, we know that if a user does not get their email, it is likely to be found in the spam pile. As modelers, we want to avoid a user losing out on their emails. The same logic could then apply to SMS messages if there were a spam folder.

Building off the email example, a high recall would mean a user is unlikely to see spam in their inbox. It is how good we are at predicting spam. But what if we want a model that gives us the best of both worlds?

If our goal is to find a balance between precision and recall, then we want to focus on the harmonic mean between precision and recall. This is known as F-score and luckily it is easy to interpret for a binary classification task.

To continue with our conclusions, both Random Forests and Neural Networks seem to yield the best precision scores. AdaBoost and support vector machines give us a high recall. If we want to focus on both metrics, AdaBoost and Neural Networks seem to have the most promise.

Future directions for research may be additional data preprocessing steps (i.e. bag of words models, lexical normalization), using pre-trained word embeddings such as Word2Vec and GloVe, and utilizing different neural network architectures such as convolutional, recurrent, and hierarchical neural networks.
